<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Cases</strong> is the collection of isolated, machine-checkable cases that are the
    <strong>source of truth for protocol conformity</strong> — the same artifacts that drive documentation
    examples also verify that an implementation honours a standard. A case is data, not code: a portable
    artifact another tool can consume, run, and check, so conformity is something you <em>prove</em>, not
    assert.
  </p>
  <p>
    Its first standard is the <strong>Mock Contract</strong> — the portable schema for the mock &amp;
    service-proxy dev-service. The same interaction-bearing artifact that drives a development-time HTTP mock
    is the one verified against the real service for drift, with Web Cases as the verification home. That is
    the &ldquo;one contract, two uses&rdquo; move: <strong>schema-validation is not contract-verification</strong>,
    so the artifact carries consumer <em>interactions</em>, not just a response shape.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">The problem it solves</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      Mock definitions and contract tests are written twice, in two incompatible dialects, and drift apart:
      the mock says one thing, the real service does another, and nothing catches it. Web Cases makes the
      <strong>portable artifact</strong> the single source — one document drives the mock <em>and</em> the
      drift-check. The dev mock and the contract suite can no longer disagree because they are the same file.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

