{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-mock-contract"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Mock Contract Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    The standard is the <strong>schema, not the server</strong>. A Mock Contract is a portable document of
    consumer <strong>interactions</strong>. Each interaction matches a request and pairs it with an agreed
    response whose <em>shape</em> is anchored on OpenAPI and whose dev-time <em>behavior</em> (latency, fault,
    conditional, response-kind, auth) lives in a behavior layer on top. The server that serves it is a
    swappable provider; the artifact is the only lock.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The portable artifact — committed to the repo, consumed by ANY conformant server or drift-checker.
interface MockContract {
  service: string;                 // logical service id → resolves to a base URL / proxy target
  openapi?: string;                // optional ref to the OpenAPI doc the shapes anchor on
  interactions: Interaction[];     // interaction-bearing: the artifact IS the contract (Pact/BDCT)
}

// One interaction = a consumer expectation: given a request, the agreed response + dev-time behavior.
interface Interaction {
  description: string;             // Pact-style label, e.g. "a request for an existing user"
  request: RequestMatch;           // method + path template + query/header/body predicates
  response: ResponseSpec;          // the agreed response — shape anchored on OpenAPI
  behavior?: BehaviorLayer;        // what OpenAPI cannot express (omit ⇒ a plain mock)
  kind?: 'mock' | 'proxy' | 'record';  // response-kind; default 'mock'
}

// ── Response shape: anchored on OpenAPI, never restated ─────────────────────────
interface ResponseSpec {
  status: number;
  schema?: OpenAPIRef | JSONSchema;  // $ref:'#/components/schemas/User' or inline
  example?: unknown;                 // the concrete mock body
  headers?: Record<string, string>;
}

// ── Behavior layer: the dev-time concerns OpenAPI has no vocabulary for ─────────
interface BehaviorLayer {
  latencyMs?: number | LatencyDistribution;  // fixed delay or a distribution
  fault?: FaultInjection;                    // forced error
  conditions?: ConditionalRule[];            // first-that-matches: vary by the live request
  auth?: AuthSpec;                           // fake bearer / OAuth; stateless unless session opted in
}

interface FaultInjection {
  status: number;                  // e.g. 401, 500
  body?: unknown;                  // the chosen error body
  rate?: number;                   // 0..1 probability (chaos); default 1 (always)
}

// Conditional responses reuse the first-that-accepts pattern: rules are tried in order,
// the first whose `when` matches the live request wins, iteration stops.
interface ConditionalRule {
  when: RequestMatch;
  respond: ResponseSpec & { behavior?: BehaviorLayer };
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One data-defined artifact:</strong> the contract is JSON, so a second server (or a drift-checker) consumes the same file — exactly the portability MSW-style code-defined mocks forfeit. The protocol is the only lock.</li>
    <li><strong>OpenAPI-anchored, not OpenAPI-bounded:</strong> the response <em>shape</em> borrows OpenAPI (by <code>$ref</code> into an existing doc, or inline), and the behavior layer adds the dev-time axes — latency, fault, conditional, response-kind, auth — OpenAPI was never meant to carry.</li>
    <li><strong>Proxy is a response-kind, not a sibling standard:</strong> <code>kind: 'proxy'</code> forwards to the real backend, <code>'record'</code> proxies-and-captures to seed mocks from live traffic, <code>'mock'</code> serves the spec. Mixed per-interaction on one service.</li>
    <li><strong>Stateless by default:</strong> auth issues a fake bearer/OAuth token without server state; a session is an explicit opt-in, because a stateless dev mock is reproducible and parallel-safe.</li>
    <li><strong>Runtime overrides stay out of the artifact:</strong> CORS-bypass, per-service on/off, and forced status are server/console/header/param overrides applied at request time — they tune a running provider, they are not part of the portable contract.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="two-uses" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">One contract, two uses — and why interactions, not shapes</h4>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    The same artifact drives the dev mock <em>and</em> verifies the real service for drift, with Web Cases as
    the verification home. This only holds because each entry is a consumer <strong>interaction</strong>
    (Pact/BDCT), not just an OpenAPI shape:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Schema-validation ≠ contract-verification.</strong> A shape check proves a payload is well-formed; it does <em>not</em> prove a real consumer depends on a field, nor that the provider still honours a specific interaction. Shape-only drift reports green while a real dependency silently breaks.</li>
    <li><strong>Drift is checked at the interaction level:</strong> Web Cases replays each interaction's request against the real provider and compares the live response to the agreed one — the consumer-driven verification Pact names, generalized to BDCT (an existing OpenAPI provider contract verified against consumer interactions).</li>
    <li><strong>Use A — mock:</strong> a conformant dev server reads the contract and serves the interactions, with the behavior layer applied.</li>
    <li><strong>Use B — drift-check:</strong> the same interactions are verified against the live service in Web Cases; a mismatch is a contract breach, surfaced before it reaches production.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Cases owns the <em>portable, checkable artifact</em> — not the server, the console, or the policy it
    verifies. Those compose with neighbouring work:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Reference dev server (<a href="/backlog/332-mock-proxy-dev-server-provider/">#332</a>)</strong> — the swappable provider that reads a Mock Contract and serves mock / proxy / record; the schema is what makes it swappable.</li>
    <li><strong>Mock console (<a href="/backlog/333-mock-proxy-console-surface/">#333</a>)</strong> — config editor + call monitor + per-service toggles; the runtime override surface, not part of the portable artifact.</li>
    <li><strong>Drift-check (<a href="/backlog/334-mock-vs-real-drift-check-webcases/">#334</a>)</strong> — verifies the interaction-bearing artifact against the real service inside Web Cases; the second of the two uses.</li>
    <li><strong>OpenAPI</strong> — borrowed substrate for the response shape; the Mock Contract references it rather than restating schemas.</li>
    <li><strong>Provider/consumer graph (<a href="/backlog/092-provider-consumer-graph-platform-manager/">#092</a>)</strong> — a verified contract is one edge in the cross-team seam graph; drift-checking proves the edge still holds.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Cases is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The <strong>Mock Contract</strong> schema — the portable,
    interaction-bearing artifact — is specified here, with its three forks ratified in
    <a href="/backlog/107-mock-proxy-dev-service/">#107</a>. The reference dev server, the console, and the
    drift-check are the first planned builds on top of this contract.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>The conditional-rule predicate language — a small JSON match grammar, or a sandboxed expression?</li>
    <li>Whether the interaction-bearing artifact reuses an existing Web Cases case format or defines a thin superset for the HTTP-interaction shape.</li>
    <li>The latency-distribution vocabulary (fixed / uniform / normal / fixed+jitter) — borrow an existing chaos-tool grammar or define a minimal one.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
